  <section>
    <h2>Always visible</h2>
    <p>Pass <code>auto-hide="never"</code> for a bar that stays painted. Useful when the affordance is more important than the chrome budget.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="scroll-area scroll-area--bordered" data-stisla-scroll-area data-stisla-scroll-area-auto-hide="never" style="height: 14rem;">
      <div style="padding: 1rem;">
        <p>A persistent scrollbar reads more like a native desktop pattern, and pairs well with long content that benefits from a visible position indicator at rest.</p>
        <p>Trade-off is a permanent chrome stripe along the edge, even when the content has nothing to scroll past the fold. Pick based on the surface.</p>
        <p>The cascade still respects per-axis overrides, so a track that hides on x and stays on y is one extra attribute.</p>
        <p>Reduced-motion users skip the fade entirely either way, since the transition runs through the same prefers-reduced-motion gate as the rest of the system.</p>
        <p>The handle still grows and shrinks with the viewport-to-content ratio, so the position read stays honest as content updates.</p>
        <p>Click-to-track jumps the handle to the position you clicked. Hold a click on the track to keep paging in that direction.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Tinted</h2>
    <p>Override the handle vars in a parent scope to retune the bar paint to the surface's accent. The cascade scopes the change.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="scroll-area scroll-area--bordered" data-stisla-scroll-area data-stisla-scroll-area-auto-hide="never"
         style="height: 14rem;
                --scroll-area-bar-size: 0.875rem;
                --scroll-area-handle-bg: color-mix(in oklch, var(--st-primary) 35%, transparent);
                --scroll-area-handle-bg-hover: color-mix(in oklch, var(--st-primary) 55%, transparent);
                --scroll-area-handle-bg-active: var(--st-primary);">
      <div style="padding: 1rem;">
        <p>The handle paints from a primary mix at rest, deepens on hover, and lands on the solid intent on active. The track sits transparent so the parent surface reads through.</p>
        <p>Same pattern works for success, danger, info, or any custom token a parent scope publishes. Set the three handle vars once and every scroll-area inside the scope picks the new tone up.</p>
        <p>The bar width here is bumped a notch to make the color read at a glance. Defaults stay narrow so the chrome reads as plumbing rather than decoration.</p>
        <p>Density still applies through the surrounding scale, so a compact view shrinks the surface around the bar without retuning the bar itself.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Events</h2>
    <p><code>stisla:scroll-area:destroyed</code> fires on the root when the underlying OverlayScrollbars instance is torn down (the component is destroyed or unmounted). Use it to detach any consumer-side listeners or refs you held against the scroll area.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Customization</h2>
    <p>Override the <code>--scroll-area-*</code> vars on the element, in a parent scope, or on <code>:root</code>. The cascade scopes the change.</p>

    <h3>Surface</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Variable</th><th>Use</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>--scroll-area-radius</code></td><td>Root corner radius. The clip prevents content from bleeding past rounded corners.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Bar geometry</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Variable</th><th>Use</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>--scroll-area-bar-size</code></td><td>Handle thickness. Track grows by the padding on either side.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--scroll-area-bar-padding</code></td><td>Gap between handle and viewport edge.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--scroll-area-bar-radius</code></td><td>Track and handle corner radius. Pill is intentional.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--scroll-area-handle-min-size</code></td><td>Floor on handle length so the affordance stays grabbable even with long content.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Paint</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Variable</th><th>Use</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>--scroll-area-track-bg</code></td><td>Track fill. Default lets the parent surface read through.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--scroll-area-handle-bg</code></td><td>Handle rest fill.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--scroll-area-handle-bg-hover</code></td><td>Handle hover fill.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--scroll-area-handle-bg-active</code></td><td>Handle dragging fill.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Border</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Variable</th><th>Use</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>--scroll-area-border-width</code></td><td>Frame border thickness, applied by <code>.scroll-area--bordered</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>--scroll-area-border-color</code></td><td>Frame border color.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p><code>.scroll-area--bordered</code> adds a hairline border for surfaces that need a frame around the scrolling region. The handle fade is gated behind <code>prefers-reduced-motion</code> so reduced-motion users skip it.</p>
  </section>
{% endblock %}
